        <section id="health-safety">
            <h2>HEALTH & SAFETY</h2>
            
            <h3>Altitude Considerations:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Kathmandu: 1,400m (minimal risk)</li>
                <li>Highest day trip: 2,732m (Shivapuri)</li>
                <li>Stay hydrated, ascend gradually</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Medical Preparations:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Travel insurance with adventure sports coverage (strongly recommended; often required by operators)</li>
                <li>Vaccines: Hepatitis A & Typhoid recommended; Hepatitis B per risk; Japanese Encephalitis only for long-stay/rural exposure</li>
                <li>Bring: Diamox (altitude), Imodium, antibiotics</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Emergency Contacts:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Tourist Police: 1144</li>
                <li>CIWEC Hospital (Expat clinic): +977-1-4524111 / 4524242 / 4535232</li>
                <li>Embassy contacts</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="weather">
            <h2>WEATHER IN APRIL</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Temperature: 10-25°C (50-77°F)</li>
                <li>Clear mornings, possible afternoon clouds</li>
                <li>Expect some showers; rainfall increases through April</li>
                <li>Mornings are clearest - best mountain views before 10 AM</li>
                <li>Perfect trekking conditions</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="food-drink">
            <h2>MUST-TRY FOOD & DRINK</h2>
            
            <h3>Essential Dish: Dal Bhat</h3>
            <div class="important-note" style="background-color: #e8f5e8; border-color: #5a8f5b;">
                <p>No trip to Nepal is complete without <strong>dal bhat</strong> — the classic staple of rice (bhat) and lentil soup (dal), usually served with vegetable curries (tarkari), pickles (achar), sometimes meat, and greens.</p>
                <p>What makes dal bhat exciting is how each region adds its twist: different vegetables, spices, herbs, even mountain herbs like <em>jimbu</em> (a Himalayan herb) in upper regions.</p>
                <p><strong>Trekker's tip:</strong> When you're trekking or in village guesthouses, a second or third serving is often included — locals say "dal bhat power 24 hour" to reflect strength from eating abundant servings!</p>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Other Must-Try Local Dishes:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Momos</strong> — Himalayan dumplings (steamed or fried) filled with meat or vegetables. Ubiquitous and always a good idea! <span class="price">$2-4 per plate</span></li>
                <li><strong>Kwati</strong> — A mixed bean soup, popular especially during festivals. Rich in protein and perfect after a trek.</li>
                <li><strong>Chatamari</strong> — A Newari-style rice crepe (sometimes called "Nepali pizza"). Best found in traditional Newari restaurants in Kathmandu.</li>
                <li><strong>Sel Roti</strong> — Ring-shaped sweet bread, crispy outside, soft inside. Great with tea!</li>
                <li><strong>Thukpa</strong> — Tibetan noodle soup, perfect for cool evenings</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Where to Find the Best Food:</h3>
            <div class="tour-option">
                <h4>Thamel Area Recommendations:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Mustang Thakali Kitchen</strong> — Authentic dal bhat experience</li>
                    <li><strong>Momo Hut</strong> — Best momos in various styles</li>
                    <li><strong>Bhojan Griha</strong> — Traditional Newari cuisine with cultural show</li>
                    <li><strong>OR2K</strong> — Middle Eastern/Israeli food (for when you need a break from local cuisine)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Local Drinks to Experience:</h3>
            <div class="tour-option">
                <h4>Alcoholic Beverages:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Aila</strong> — Traditional distilled spirit made from rice, millet, or barley. Found in local guesthouses and during cultural evenings. <em>Sip cautiously - it's potent!</em></li>
                    <li><strong>Marpha Brandy</strong> — Apple brandy from the Mustang region. Sweet and smooth, perfect after dinner.</li>
                    <li><strong>Tongba</strong> — Hot millet beer served in wooden vessels, popular in eastern Nepal</li>
                    <li><strong>Raksi</strong> — Clear distilled beverage similar to sake</li>
                    <li><strong>Local beer</strong> — Try Everest, Gorkha, or Nepal Ice brands <span class="price">$2-3 per bottle</span></li>
                </ul>
                
                <h4>Non-Alcoholic Options:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Masala Chiya</strong> — Spiced milk tea, perfect for mornings</li>
                    <li><strong>Lassi</strong> — Yogurt-based drink (sweet or salty)</li>
                    <li><strong>Fresh juices</strong> — Mango, apple, orange widely available</li>
                    <li><strong>Butter tea</strong> — Traditional in higher altitudes</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="important-note">
                <strong>Food Safety Tips:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Stick to cooked foods and avoid raw vegetables initially</li>
                    <li>Dal bhat is usually safe as it's freshly cooked and hot</li>
                    <li>Drink only bottled or boiled water</li>
                    <li>Popular restaurants with high turnover are generally safer</li>
                    <li>Carry probiotics and basic stomach medications</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Food Tour Option:</h3>
            <div class="tour-option">
                <p><strong>Book on Viator:</strong> "Kathmandu Food Walking Tour" <span class="price">($25-35 pp)</span></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>3-4 hour guided tour through local markets and eateries</li>
                    <li>Try 6-8 different dishes with explanations</li>
                    <li>Includes drinks and all food</li>
                    <li>Great for Day 7 before departure</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="considerations">
            <h2>SPECIAL CONSIDERATIONS FOR ACTIVE TRAVELERS</h2>
            
            <h3>Fitness & Pacing:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>All suggested hikes are moderate with options to shorten</li>
                <li>Guides will adjust pace to your comfort level</li>
                <li>Most treks include rest stops every 45-60 minutes</li>
                <li>Downhill options available for most mountain hikes</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Health & Altitude:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Maximum day trip altitude: 2,732m (generally safe)</li>
                <li>Stay hydrated - carry 2L water minimum</li>
                <li>Consider bringing trekking poles for stability</li>
                <li>Pack any regular medications plus extras</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Comfort Upgrades:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Request e-bikes for cycling tours</li>
                <li>Book private tours for flexible timing</li>
                <li>Consider upgrading to premium hotels ($80-120/night)</li>
                <li>Hire porter for day hikes ($20/day) to carry packs</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Insurance:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Ensure coverage up to 6,000m altitude</li>
                <li>Verify any restrictions for adventure activities</li>
                <li>Helicopter evacuation coverage recommended</li>
                <li>Check pre-existing condition coverage</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="tips">
            <h2>PRO TIPS</h2>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Money:</strong> ATMs available but bring USD cash backup</li>
                <li><strong>SIM Card:</strong> Buy at airport (Ncell or NTC) - SIM ≈ NPR 100 + tourist data pack NPR 500-1,300 (~$4-$10 total)</li>
                <li><strong>Bargaining:</strong> Expected in markets, not in restaurants</li>
                <li><strong>Tipping:</strong> Guides $5-10/day, drivers $3-5/day</li>
                <li><strong>Power:</strong> Bring universal adapter (Type C, D, M)</li>
                <li><strong>Best Photo Spots:</strong> Sunrise from hotel rooftop, sunset from temples</li>
                <li><strong>Cultural Note:</strong> Remove shoes in temples, dress modestly</li>
            </ol>
        </section>

